{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 17.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 19.5 (Macintosh)", "creationdate": "2025-06-30T13:23:51+01:00", "moddate": "2025-06-30T13:23:54+01:00", "trapped": "/False", "source": "corpus\\autistic-spectrum-v4.pdf", "total_pages": 47, "page": 33, "page_label": "34"}, "page_content": "34\nwww.bristolautismsupport.org/all-about-your-autism-diagnosis\nAutistic children often already know they are different and are aware of their \nchallenges. Telling them they are autistic and what this means for them in a \npositive way will help them understand themselves better. Help your child gain \nan understanding of what autism means for them, their differences, talents and \nchallenges, and coping strategies.\nThe cards can be used \nto start a conversation \nabout autism and \npersonalise autism for \nyour child.\nSometimes autistic people can struggle with their autism diagnosis, and so the \nSpectrum Gaming community members have made a video about it.\n\u2018Good To Be Me\u2019 music video:\nwww.youtube.com/watch?v=0pibDq98raQ\nThe \u2018Know Yourself series\u2019 offers videos, PDFs and worksheets to support autistic \nyoung people develop an understanding of themselves and what being autistic means \nto them.\nwww.autism.org.uk/advice-and-guidance/topics/resources-for-autistic-teenagers", "type": "Document"}}